The optical properties of N-CDs are displayed in Fig. 4
                        . N-CDs show broad absorption from 200 to 400nm. N-CDs exhibit a strong absorption peak at 282nm together with a shoulder around 310nm. The peak at 282nm is ascribed to p-p* transition of the CC bands of localized sp2 clusters in the core, whereas the shoulder is due to n-p* transition of the CO bands of carboxyl groups on the shell of N-CDs. To further explore the optical properties of N-CDs, the PL spectra of N-CDs under different excitation wavelengths were measured. With increasing excitation wavelength, the PL intensity of N-CDs first increases and then decreases, and the PL peak of N-CDs shows a red shift (the inset in Fig. 4B), indicating that both PL intensity and peak are dependent on excitation. N-CDs show a strong PL at 402nm excited at 340nm. Using quinine sulfate as the reference, the fluorescence QY of the as-prepared N-CDs is measured to be 22.5%, which is higher than CDs prepared by some other eco-friendly methods (Table 1
                        ).
